explanation:
## Concept
HTTP/2 suffers from head-of-line blocking at TCP level - one lost packet blocks all streams. QUIC solves this by using UDP as transport and implementing reliability, congestion control, and stream multiplexing at the application layer.

## Implementation
```go
// QUIC stream independence
for _, stream := range conn.Streams() {
    go func(s quic.Stream) {
        // Each stream processes independently
        data, err := io.ReadAll(s)
        // Lost packets only affect this stream
        handleStreamData(s.ID(), data)
    }(stream)
}

// Connection-level recovery
conn.HandleLostPacket(packetID)
// Other streams continue unaffected
```

## Trade-offs
**Pros:**
- No head-of-line blocking between streams
- Faster connection establishment (0-RTT)
- Better mobility support (connection migration)

**Cons:**
- Higher CPU usage (user-space reliability)
- More complex implementation
- Potential NAT/UDP blocking issues

## Pitfalls
- UDP may be blocked by corporate firewalls
- Increased packet overhead vs TCP
- Debugging complexity with custom reliability layer
